{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}
[[File:Upper Penninsula Michigan State Fairgrounds Buildings.jpg|thumb|right|Buildings and sign]]
The '''Upper Peninsula State Fair''' is a fair held annually in the [[Upper Peninsula of Michigan|Upper Peninsula]] of the U.S. state of [[Michigan]]. It is held in [[Escanaba, Michigan|Escanaba]] in mid-August of each year.<ref>{{cite book |title = Michigan Yesterday & Today |last = Domm |first =  Robert W. |date = 2009 |publisher = MBI Pub. Co. LLC and Voyageur Press |isbn = 0760333858 |location = Minneapolis |oclc = 271105447 |page = |ref= harv }}{{page needed|date=January 2018}}</ref> Prior to 2010, it was one of two official [[state fair]]s in Michigan.

In April 1927, Michigan Governor [[Fred W. Green]] signed Act 89, which stated that "an annual state fair at the City of Escanaba, which shall have for its main purpose the exploiting, and encouragement of improved methods in agriculture and industrial pursuits I hereby authorize." The opening day of the first Upper Peninsula State Fair was September 17, 1928. The original price for a ticket to the fair was 50 cents for adults, decreasing to 25 cents after 6pm.<ref>{{Cite news |url = http://www.dailypress.net/life/features/2017/08/the-start-of-the-upper-peninsula-state-fair/ |title = The Start of the Upper Peninsula State Fair |work = Daily Press |location = Escanaba, MI |language = en-US |access-date = January 24, 2018 }}</ref> The present site encompasses {{convert|120|acre|km2}} of land and 24 buildings. It also includes nearly 700 campsites.

In 2010, the state ceased funding for the fair and the downstate [[Michigan State Fair]] due to budget problems. Control of fair operations has been passed onto the U.P. State Fair Authority which includes representatives from each county in the U.P. and the Hannahville Indian Community.<ref>{{cite news |first= Jenny |last= Lancour |date= August 22, 2009 |url= http://www.dailypress.net/page/content.detail/id/514425.html/U.P.-State-Fair-changes-hands |title= U.P. State Fair Changes Hands |work= Daily Press |location= Escanaba, MI }}</ref> Despite the discontinuation of the downstate Michigan State Fair, which has failed to attract outside funding and struggled with sharply dropping attendance through the years, the U.P. State Fair will continue on into the foreseeable future.

The fair highlights the lumberjack history of the region through the Great Lakes Timber Show featuring logrolling, speedclimbing, sawing, and axe-throwing demonstrations.<ref>{{harvp|Domm|2009|p=}}.{{page needed|date=January 2018}}</ref>

The 2017 Fair set a record of attendance of 87,750 according to Executive Director of the Delta Chamber of Commerce, Vickie Micheau.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.miningjournal.net/news/local/2017/09/u-p-state-fair-numbers-up-over-2016-best-year-ever/ |title = U.P. State Fair Numbers up over 2016, Best Year Ever |work = [[The Mining Journal]]  |location = Marquette, MI |language = en-US |access-date = January 24, 2018 }}</ref>

